library(readr)
bc = read_delim("GEN00067701-barcodes.txt", delim=" ", progress=FALSE)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   barcode = col_character(),
##   index = col_character(),
##   barcodeq = col_double(),
##   indexq = col_double()
## )
library(dplyr)
grouped = bc %>%
  group_by(barcode, index) %>%
  summarise(count=n(), bcq=mean(barcodeq), iq=mean(indexq))

Summary stats

There are 255727 unique barcode-index pairs and of those 6024 are seen more than 10 times.

We can see below that there is are a small set of barcode-index pairs that are represented a high number of times.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(grouped, aes(count)) + geom_histogram() + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_log10() + scale_y_sqrt()

Known barcodes

Now we’ll mark up the barcode-index pair with whether or not these are some of the known sequences. The indexes we found correspond to the reverse complement column in the index file and the barcodes correspond to the sense column in the barcode file.

kbc = read_csv("../metadata/barcode.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   id = col_integer(),
##   sense = col_character(),
##   anti_sense = col_character()
## )
kin = read_csv("../metadata/index.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   id = col_integer(),
##   seq = col_character(),
##   rc = col_character()
## )
grouped$kin = grouped$index %in% kin$rc
grouped$kbc = grouped$barcode %in% kbc$anti_sense
grouped$known = grouped$kin & grouped$kbc
grouped$known = ifelse(grouped$known, "known", "unknown")

Here we do a bunch of transformations to get the expected index-barcode pairs in a useful format. We take all the expected barcode matchings for each experiment and each pool separately, and then determine which indexes should have which barcodes. Then we combine them all together at the end.

expected = read_csv("../metadata/GEN00067701-indexpairs.csv", progress=FALSE)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   id = col_integer(),
##   sense = col_character(),
##   anti_sense = col_character(),
##   bcid = col_character()
## )
mcneu = read_tsv("../metadata/McNeu.tsv", progress=FALSE) %>%
  mutate(pool="McNeu Pool") %>%
  left_join(expected, by=c("pool"="bcid")) %>%
  select(-pool)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   bcid = col_integer()
## )
hmler = read_tsv("../metadata/HMLER.tsv") %>%
  mutate(pool="HMLER Pool") %>%
  left_join(expected, by=c("pool"="bcid")) %>%
  select(-pool)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   bcid = col_integer()
## )
poola = read_tsv("../metadata/PoolA.csv") %>%
  mutate(pool="Pool A") %>%
  left_join(expected, by=c("pool"="bcid")) %>%
  select(-pool)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   bcid = col_integer()
## )
expected = subset(expected, !bcid %in% c("McNeu Pool", "HMLER Pool", "Pool A"))
expected$bcid = as.integer(expected$bcid)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
expected = expected %>% bind_rows(mcneu, hmler, poola) %>%
  left_join(kbc, by=c("bcid"="id")) %>%
  select(anti_sense.y, anti_sense.x) %>%
  na.omit()
colnames(expected) = c("ebarcode", "eindex")
expected$pair = paste(expected$ebarcode, expected$eindex, sep=":")
write_csv(expected, "expected-reformat.csv")

That was a bunch of joining and merging, so let’s make sure we did it correctly. We’re expecting 1 index to have 1 barcode, 3 indexes to have 6 barcodes (Pool A), 11 indexes to have 30 sequences (McNeu pool), 3 sequences to have 33 barcodes (McNeu pool) and 2 indexes to have 0 barcodes. That is a total of 448 barcode index pairs. There are 448 rows in the expected barcode data frame, once we are done with all the merging, so it looks like we did the merging correctly.

grouped$pair = paste(grouped$barcode, grouped$index, sep=":")
grouped$expected = grouped$pair %in% expected$pair
known = subset(grouped, known == "known")

We only only see 404 of the 448 expected barcode-index pairs in this dataset. Some indexes are missing expected barcodes:

missing_pairs = expected %>%
  mutate(present=pair %in% grouped$pair) %>%
  group_by(eindex, present) %>% summarise(count=n())
ggplot(missing_pairs, aes(eindex, count, color=present)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("") +
  theme(axis.text.x  = element_text(angle=90))

I wrote out the barcode-index pairs with counts, the mean of the barcode quality (bcq), the mean of the index quality (iq), whether or not the index is a known index (kin), whether or not the barcode is a known barcode (kin), and whether or not the barcode-index pair is expected (known).

This table is here All barcode index

write.table(grouped, file="all-barcode-index-unfiltered.csv", col.names=TRUE, row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE, sep=",")

Now we can see if we mark up the barcode-index pairs with whether or not they are from the known barcode and known index files, we find that there are 892 barcode-index pairs and 404 expected barcode-index pairs.

If we plot the histograms separating out whether they are a known or unknown barcode-index pair, we can see that the known barcode-index pairs have many more reads associated with them than the unknown barcode-index pairs.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(grouped, aes(count)) + geom_histogram() + theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(~known) +
  scale_x_log10() + scale_y_sqrt() +
  ylab("number of barcode-index pairs")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We can see that the PHRED quality of the known barcode-index pairs has a tight distribution:

ggplot(grouped, aes(bcq, iq)) + geom_point() + theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(~known) +
  ylab("mean PHRED quality of index") +
  xlab("mean PHRED quality of barcode")

Here you can see that if we filter for only known barcodes and indexes, they tend to have both a high index and barcode quality compared to unknown sequences.

ggplot(grouped, aes(bcq, iq, color=known)) + geom_point(size=0.5) + theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(~kin+kbc) +
  ylab("mean PHRED quality of index") +
  xlab("mean PHRED quality of barcode")

If we look at the expected barcode-index pairings, we can see that there is not much of a difference in the distribution of quality of the barcode-index pairs for the pairs we expect (TRUE) and the pairs we do not expect (FALSE). Filtering on quality will not help these results.

ggplot(subset(grouped, known == "known"), aes(bcq, iq)) +
  geom_point(size=0.5) + theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(~expected) +
  ylab("mean PHRED quality of index") +
  xlab("mean PHRED quality of barcode")

We can see that the barcode-index pairs have about an order of magnitude less counts when they are not expected than when they are expected.

ggplot(subset(grouped, known == "known"), aes(count)) +
  geom_histogram() + theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(~expected) +
  scale_x_log10()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Barcodes per index

We generally see more barcodes than we are expecting per index.

expected_counts = expected %>% group_by(eindex) %>% summarise(nexpected=n())
barcode_per_index = known %>% group_by(index) %>% summarise(nbarcodes = n()) %>%
  left_join(expected_counts, by=c("index"="eindex")) %>%
  tidyr::gather("type", "count", 2:3)
index_per_barcode = known %>% group_by(barcode) %>% summarise(nindex = n())
ggplot(barcode_per_index, aes(index, count, fill=type)) +
  geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
  xlab("")

Barcodes counts for each index

We see every index with every barcode at least once. Here we color the plots by if they are the pair we expected or not.

ggplot(known, aes(barcode, count, fill=expected)) +
  facet_wrap(~index) + geom_bar(stat='identity') +
  scale_y_sqrt() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.ticks = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_blank())

These aren’t lining up at all with what we were expecting, it looks a lot worse than the previous library.

Output tables

The first table has the expected barcode-index pairings, reformatted to be easy to use in the script.

Expected barcode-index pairs file (reformatted)

This table is all of the identified barcode-index pairs from the sequence data (everything that matched the regex). It is unfiltered, and has columns indicating whether the barcode was known ‘kbc’ the index was known ‘kin’, both were known ‘known’ and if the barcode-index pair is expected ‘expected’. The count column is the total number of times we saw this barcode-index pairing.

Barcode-index pairings (unfiltered)

Summary

Something is up, we are seeing barcodes in all kinds of samples we are not expecting. This isn’t simple crosstalk, because if that was the case we would see a low level of cross contamination but still see the main barcode signals popping out like we did in the first set of samples. It is entirely possible that I have screwed something up, but if I am, I can’t figure out where it is happening.
